    soWhatNowWhat: {
      whatDoesThisMean: 'Isaiah 3-4 reveals a God who sees through the costume. The luxury, the status markers, the institutional supports we lean on — God names them for what they are: layers we have added to the self, often at someone else\'s expense. The stripping is not nihilistic — it is preparatory. God does not remove the finery and leave the person standing in the cold. God removes the finery and provides a covering that no human hand can manufacture: the Branch, the glory, the canopy. The movement from chapter 3 to chapter 4 is the movement of grace: exposure, then clothing; vulnerability, then shelter; shame, then beauty.',
      soWhat: 'Examine your layers. Not to despise them, but to name them honestly: which of your identity markers — your title, your possessions, your reputation, your curated image — exist at the expense of someone else\'s dignity? Which layers are you most afraid to lose? The one that creates the most fear is likely the one most in need of examination. And notice the direction of the passage: the stripping is never the final word. The question is not whether you are willing to be stripped, but whether you trust the one who promises a canopy on the other side.',
      nowWhat: 'This week, choose one concrete action that moves wealth or power from your hands toward someone who has been "crushed" or "ground down" by the systems you participate in. Not charity from a distance — proximity. Share a meal with someone invisible. Advocate for someone whose case no one takes. Examine one purchase, one investment, one pattern of consumption and ask: whose labor paid for this? At whose expense does my comfort exist? Let the discomfort of the question lead you — not to guilt, which paralyzes, but to justice, which acts. Then sit under the canopy of 4:5-6 and let the God who strips also cover you.',
    },

